const _astro_dataLayerContent = [["Map",1,2,9,10,148,149,190,191],"meta::meta",["Map",3,4,5,6,7,8],"astro-version","5.17.3","content-config-digest","dfb4d59d8ee43855","astro-config-digest","{\"root\":{},\"srcDir\":{},\"publicDir\":{},\"outDir\":{},\"cacheDir\":{},\"compressHTML\":true,\"base\":\"/\",\"trailingSlash\":\"ignore\",\"output\":\"static\",\"scopedStyleStrategy\":\"attribute\",\"build\":{\"format\":\"directory\",\"client\":{},\"server\":{},\"assets\":\"_astro\",\"serverEntry\":\"entry.mjs\",\"redirects\":false,\"inlineStylesheets\":\"auto\",\"concurrency\":1},\"server\":{\"open\":false,\"host\":true,\"port\":4321,\"streaming\":true,\"allowedHosts\":[]},\"redirects\":{},\"image\":{\"endpoint\":{\"route\":\"/_image\"},\"service\":{\"entrypoint\":\"astro/assets/services/sharp\",\"config\":{}},\"domains\":[],\"remotePatterns\":[],\"responsiveStyles\":false},\"devToolbar\":{\"enabled\":true},\"markdown\":{\"syntaxHighlight\":{\"type\":\"shiki\",\"excludeLangs\":[\"math\"]},\"shikiConfig\":{\"langs\":[],\"langAlias\":{},\"theme\":\"github-dark\",\"themes\":{},\"wrap\":false,\"transformers\":[]},\"remarkPlugins\":[],\"rehypePlugins\":[],\"remarkRehype\":{},\"gfm\":true,\"smartypants\":true},\"security\":{\"checkOrigin\":false,\"allowedDomains\":[]},\"env\":{\"schema\":{},\"validateSecrets\":false},\"experimental\":{\"clientPrerender\":false,\"contentIntellisense\":false,\"headingIdCompat\":false,\"preserveScriptOrder\":false,\"liveContentCollections\":false,\"csp\":false,\"staticImportMetaEnv\":false,\"chromeDevtoolsWorkspace\":false,\"failOnPrerenderConflict\":false,\"svgo\":false},\"legacy\":{\"collections\":false}}","work",["Map",11,12,80,81,126,127],"fuel-intel-hub",{id:11,data:13,body:21,filePath:22,digest:23,rendered:24,legacyId:79},{title:14,year:15,industry:16,category:17,summary:18,thumbnail:19,featured:20},"Fuel Intelligence Hub",2025,"Energy","SAAS Platform","Intelligence platform that helps fuel suppliers optimize supply, pricing, and customer performance, driving customer retention and opening new revenue opportunities in the energy sector.","/images/thumb-fuel-hub.png",true,"## Problem + Goal\n\n**User Problem:** Analysts spent hours reconciling fragmented fuel data and could not make timely trading or operational decisions.\n\n**Business Goal:** Launch a differentiated intelligence platform that helps fuel suppliers optimize supply, pricing, and customer performance, driving customer retention and opening new revenue opportunities in the energy sector.\n\n## Exploration: Version 1\n\nOur first wireframe direction emphasized operational oversight and regional monitoring.\n\n**What we tested:** Could analysts anchor on a broad overview dashboard to triage supply risk and competitor pressure across multiple terminals?\n\n**What we learned:** While this view was valuable for identifying risks, it largely positioned the tool as a monitoring dashboard. Users wanted to go beyond \"what is happening\" to explore \"what should I do about it?\"\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      This exploration helped validate the usefulness of a regional overview, but it also revealed a\n      positioning problem: users saw insight, but not enough support for action.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      The takeaway was not to discard operational visibility, but to make it a foundation for better\n      decision support rather than the primary value proposition.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open version 1 exploration placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-Fuel Intelligence Hub - Region Summary 1.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Version 1 exploration screen focused on operational monitoring and regional oversight\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for Version 1 wireframe direction emphasizing operational oversight and regional monitoring.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Exploration: Version 2\n\nOur second iteration shifted from reporting toward decision support by connecting operational data directly to pricing and margin levers.\n\n**What we tested:** Could supply and pricing managers use this hub to simulate scenarios, optimize prices, and align supply actions with profitability goals?\n\n**What we learned:** Analysts saw this as moving from a passive tool to an intelligence platform, helping them make proactive, financially grounded decisions rather than just track stock levels.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      This direction reframed the product from a dashboard into a working tool for operational and\n      commercial decisions. Users responded to the tighter relationship between signals, scenarios, and\n      recommended actions.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      The shift also clarified the product story internally: this was not just better reporting, it was\n      a platform for decision-making.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open version 2 exploration placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-Fuel Intelligence Hub - Copy of Terminal Detail 1.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Version 2 exploration showing decision support with pricing and margin levers\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for Version 2 concept connecting operational data to pricing, margin, and scenario-based decision support.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Initial prototypes\n\n### Prototype: Version 1\n\nWhile early wireframes explored whether analysts could triage supply risks and competitor pressure using broad overviews, the refined concepts, as seen in these first prototypes, doubled down on actionable intelligence, moving from static monitoring dashboards to scenario-driven decision support tools where supply managers and pricing managers could not only see risks but also test and implement solutions.\n\n_Note: These early prototypes used v1 of our Eco design system._\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      These prototypes helped the team pressure-test information hierarchy, workflow sequencing, and the\n      balance between operational context and pricing actions before full visual system refinement.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open initial prototype placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-wind-farm.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Initial prototype screen using Eco design system v1\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for an early coded prototype screen using Eco design system v1.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\nWe created a coded prototype, polished enough to feel real but lightweight enough to change quickly, as a hands-on tool during co-innovation workshops with pilot customers.\n\nThis approach let participants experience core workflows, give immediate feedback, and enabled us to rapidly iterate live in the sessions, validating concepts and refining priorities before moving into full-scale design and development.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open workshop prototype video placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Embedded video walkthrough of the coded prototype used in co-innovation workshops\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a left-aligned embedded video walkthrough from co-innovation workshops.</em></p>\n  </div>\n  <div>\n    <h3>Co-innovation workshop prototype</h3>\n    <p>\n      The coded prototype worked as both a conversation tool and a validation mechanism. Because it felt\n      real enough to use, stakeholders could react to workflows and decisions instead of speculating in\n      the abstract.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      That made workshops more productive and helped us refine priorities earlier, before high-cost design\n      and engineering commitments.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Results\n\n![Placeholder: Results overview image](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width results summary visual._\n\n## Supply Risk Mitigation\n\n![Placeholder: Supply Risk Mitigation image 1](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width supply risk mitigation visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Supply Risk Mitigation image 2](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a second full-width supply risk mitigation visual._\n\n## Supply Risk Mitigation: Real-Time Stock\n\n![Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 1](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 2](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 3](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 4](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual._\n\n## Supply Risk Mitigation: Scenario Modeler\n\n![Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 1](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 2](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 3](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 4](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual._\n\n## Approval Workflow\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 1](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 2](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual._\n\n## Approval Workflow\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 3](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 4](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 5](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual._\n\n## Approval Workflow Management: Modify\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 1](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 2](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual._\n\n## Approval Workflow Management: Modify\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 3](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 4](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual._\n\n## Audit Log\n\n![Placeholder: Audit Log image 1](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual._\n\n## Gallery\n\n<div class=\"masonry-gallery\">\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 12.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 1\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 17.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 2\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 24.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 3\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 33.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 4\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 40.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 5\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n![Placeholder: Audit Log image 2](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual._\n\n## Audit Log\n\n![Placeholder: Audit Log image 3](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual._\n\n![Placeholder: Audit Log image 4](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual._","src/content/work/fuel-intel-hub.md","8fa63d55f6ec739c",{html:25,metadata:26},"<h2 id=\"problem--goal\">Problem + Goal</h2>\n<p><strong>User Problem:</strong> Analysts spent hours reconciling fragmented fuel data and could not make timely trading or operational decisions.</p>\n<p><strong>Business Goal:</strong> Launch a differentiated intelligence platform that helps fuel suppliers optimize supply, pricing, and customer performance, driving customer retention and opening new revenue opportunities in the energy sector.</p>\n<h2 id=\"exploration-version-1\">Exploration: Version 1</h2>\n<p>Our first wireframe direction emphasized operational oversight and regional monitoring.</p>\n<p><strong>What we tested:</strong> Could analysts anchor on a broad overview dashboard to triage supply risk and competitor pressure across multiple terminals?</p>\n<p><strong>What we learned:</strong> While this view was valuable for identifying risks, it largely positioned the tool as a monitoring dashboard. Users wanted to go beyond “what is happening” to explore “what should I do about it?”</p>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      This exploration helped validate the usefulness of a regional overview, but it also revealed a\n      positioning problem: users saw insight, but not enough support for action.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      The takeaway was not to discard operational visibility, but to make it a foundation for better\n      decision support rather than the primary value proposition.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open version 1 exploration placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-Fuel Intelligence Hub - Region Summary 1.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Version 1 exploration screen focused on operational monitoring and regional oversight\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for Version 1 wireframe direction emphasizing operational oversight and regional monitoring.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"exploration-version-2\">Exploration: Version 2</h2>\n<p>Our second iteration shifted from reporting toward decision support by connecting operational data directly to pricing and margin levers.</p>\n<p><strong>What we tested:</strong> Could supply and pricing managers use this hub to simulate scenarios, optimize prices, and align supply actions with profitability goals?</p>\n<p><strong>What we learned:</strong> Analysts saw this as moving from a passive tool to an intelligence platform, helping them make proactive, financially grounded decisions rather than just track stock levels.</p>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      This direction reframed the product from a dashboard into a working tool for operational and\n      commercial decisions. Users responded to the tighter relationship between signals, scenarios, and\n      recommended actions.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      The shift also clarified the product story internally: this was not just better reporting, it was\n      a platform for decision-making.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open version 2 exploration placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-Fuel Intelligence Hub - Copy of Terminal Detail 1.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Version 2 exploration showing decision support with pricing and margin levers\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for Version 2 concept connecting operational data to pricing, margin, and scenario-based decision support.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"initial-prototypes\">Initial prototypes</h2>\n<h3 id=\"prototype-version-1\">Prototype: Version 1</h3>\n<p>While early wireframes explored whether analysts could triage supply risks and competitor pressure using broad overviews, the refined concepts, as seen in these first prototypes, doubled down on actionable intelligence, moving from static monitoring dashboards to scenario-driven decision support tools where supply managers and pricing managers could not only see risks but also test and implement solutions.</p>\n<p><em>Note: These early prototypes used v1 of our Eco design system.</em></p>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      These prototypes helped the team pressure-test information hierarchy, workflow sequencing, and the\n      balance between operational context and pricing actions before full visual system refinement.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open initial prototype placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-wind-farm.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Initial prototype screen using Eco design system v1\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for an early coded prototype screen using Eco design system v1.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<p>We created a coded prototype, polished enough to feel real but lightweight enough to change quickly, as a hands-on tool during co-innovation workshops with pilot customers.</p>\n<p>This approach let participants experience core workflows, give immediate feedback, and enabled us to rapidly iterate live in the sessions, validating concepts and refining priorities before moving into full-scale design and development.</p>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open workshop prototype video placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Embedded video walkthrough of the coded prototype used in co-innovation workshops\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a left-aligned embedded video walkthrough from co-innovation workshops.</em></p>\n  </div>\n  <div>\n    <h3>Co-innovation workshop prototype</h3>\n    <p>\n      The coded prototype worked as both a conversation tool and a validation mechanism. Because it felt\n      real enough to use, stakeholders could react to workflows and decisions instead of speculating in\n      the abstract.\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      That made workshops more productive and helped us refine priorities earlier, before high-cost design\n      and engineering commitments.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"results\">Results</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Results overview image\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width results summary visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"supply-risk-mitigation\">Supply Risk Mitigation</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Supply Risk Mitigation image 1\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width supply risk mitigation visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Supply Risk Mitigation image 2\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a second full-width supply risk mitigation visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"supply-risk-mitigation-real-time-stock\">Supply Risk Mitigation: Real-Time Stock</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 1\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 2\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 3\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Real-Time Stock image 4\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width real-time stock visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"supply-risk-mitigation-scenario-modeler\">Supply Risk Mitigation: Scenario Modeler</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 1\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 2\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 3\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Scenario Modeler image 4\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width scenario modeler visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"approval-workflow\">Approval Workflow</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 1\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 2\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"approval-workflow-1\">Approval Workflow</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 3\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 4\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow image 5\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"approval-workflow-management-modify\">Approval Workflow Management: Modify</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 1\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 2\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"approval-workflow-management-modify-1\">Approval Workflow Management: Modify</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 3\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Approval Workflow Management Modify image 4\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width approval workflow management visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"audit-log\">Audit Log</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Audit Log image 1\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"gallery\">Gallery</h2>\n<div class=\"masonry-gallery\">\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 12.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 1\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 17.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 2\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 24.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 3\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 33.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 4\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/work/FIH-image 40.png\" alt=\"Fuel Hub gallery image 5\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Audit Log image 2\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"audit-log-1\">Audit Log</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Audit Log image 3\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual.</em></p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Audit Log image 4\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a full-width audit log visual.</em></p>",{headings:27,localImagePaths:75,remoteImagePaths:76,frontmatter:77,imagePaths:78},[28,32,35,38,41,45,48,51,54,57,60,62,65,67,70,73],{depth:29,slug:30,text:31},2,"problem--goal","Problem + Goal",{depth:29,slug:33,text:34},"exploration-version-1","Exploration: Version 1",{depth:29,slug:36,text:37},"exploration-version-2","Exploration: Version 2",{depth:29,slug:39,text:40},"initial-prototypes","Initial prototypes",{depth:42,slug:43,text:44},3,"prototype-version-1","Prototype: Version 1",{depth:29,slug:46,text:47},"results","Results",{depth:29,slug:49,text:50},"supply-risk-mitigation","Supply Risk Mitigation",{depth:29,slug:52,text:53},"supply-risk-mitigation-real-time-stock","Supply Risk Mitigation: Real-Time Stock",{depth:29,slug:55,text:56},"supply-risk-mitigation-scenario-modeler","Supply Risk Mitigation: Scenario Modeler",{depth:29,slug:58,text:59},"approval-workflow","Approval Workflow",{depth:29,slug:61,text:59},"approval-workflow-1",{depth:29,slug:63,text:64},"approval-workflow-management-modify","Approval Workflow Management: Modify",{depth:29,slug:66,text:64},"approval-workflow-management-modify-1",{depth:29,slug:68,text:69},"audit-log","Audit Log",{depth:29,slug:71,text:72},"gallery","Gallery",{depth:29,slug:74,text:69},"audit-log-1",[],[],{title:14,year:15,industry:16,category:17,summary:18,thumbnail:19,featured:20},[],"fuel-intel-hub.md","eco-v2-redesign",{id:80,data:82,body:88,filePath:89,digest:90,rendered:91,legacyId:125},{title:83,year:15,industry:84,category:85,summary:86,thumbnail:87,featured:20},"Eco Future (v2.0)","SAAS","Design Systems","A streamlined, modern design system built to scale across sector-specific products and accelerate development.","/images/thumb-eco-v2.png","## Problem + Goal\n\n**User Problem:** Designers and developers need a cleaner, more usable system with consistent patterns, better visuals, and easier extensibility.\n\n**Business Goal:** Accelerate product delivery and reduce technical debt with a lean, modern design system that scales across DTN's products.\n\n## The Development Challenges of Eco v1.0\n\nWhile it established initial consistency, the system was rigid, bloated, and lacked the polish and patterns needed for scalable product design.\n\n- Wrapped Tailwind UI components introduced bloat and rigidity.\n- Component wrappers depended on Eco team-defined props, which meant developers could not extend or adjust behavior without waiting on the system team.\n- Overrides were cumbersome, creating friction in day-to-day workflows.\n- Rigid structure slowed iteration and encouraged shadow libraries.\n- Heavy documentation burden: significant effort was needed to document customization and workarounds, adding maintenance overhead.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      These constraints made Eco v1 difficult to scale in practice. Even when teams wanted to stay aligned\n      with the design system, the developer ergonomics often pushed them toward local exceptions and\n      one-off workarounds.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open Eco v1 development challenges placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v1 component wrapper and developer workflow challenges\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image illustrating Eco v1 development constraints or component wrapper complexity.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## The Design Challenges of Eco v1.0\n\nFrom a design perspective, Eco v1 suffered from foundational gaps that made products feel inconsistent, cluttered, and difficult to use.\n\n- No page layout conventions: products defaulted to ad-hoc app shells and inconsistent content structures.\n- Visual bloat: oversized headers, navigation, and excessive padding consumed valuable viewport space.\n- Poor color accessibility: insufficient contrast and inconsistent application of accessible color standards.\n- Lack of exemplar designs: teams had no strong reference patterns, leading to drift and uneven quality.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      Without strong layout paradigms and exemplars, product teams had too much interpretive freedom in\n      the wrong places. The result was inconsistency in both usability and visual quality across the suite.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open Eco v1 design challenges placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v1 layout inconsistency and visual bloat examples\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image showing Eco v1 visual clutter, spacing issues, or inconsistent layouts.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Component System Revamp\n\nIn Eco v2 we rebuilt our component system around ShadCN-based components, maintaining Eco's core styling for easier product adoption while addressing major gaps in flexibility, accessibility, and polish. The revamp not only simplified the developer experience but also raised the design quality across all products.\n\n- ShadCN foundation: lean, extensible components aligned to modern front-end workflows (still based on Tailwind CSS) without custom wrappers and associated bloat.\n- Eco styling preserved: ensured continuity with v1 while enabling smoother product conversion.\n- Polish improvements: redefined color palette, contrast, and spacing for better accessibility and visual clarity.\n- Cleaned-up components: simplified props, reduced bloat, and eliminated redundant wrappers.\n- Design Registry integration: improved governance, supporting both ground-up development and streamlined use with V0.\n- Future-ready pipeline: positioned Eco for faster iteration, lower technical debt, and broader cross-product consistency.\n- Introduced semantic tokens for color, typography, and spacing, improving consistency across components and enabling easier theming and accessibility compliance.\n\n## Appshell Revamp\n\nThe Eco v2 app shell was redesigned to maximize usable workspace and improve accessibility, while still providing clear navigation and hierarchy. The new shell establishes a cleaner baseline for all products.\n\n- Reduced footprint of the header and navigation, creating more space for core content.\n- Refined color contrast in both light and dark modes for improved readability and compliance with accessibility standards.\n- Simplified information hierarchy, reducing visual noise and redundant elements.\n- Improved product suite portal experience with streamlined app switching, unified cross-app notifications, and a more consistent navigation model across products.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      The updated app shell created a stronger baseline for every product team. By reducing chrome and\n      clarifying hierarchy, Eco v2 made room for content and workflows to carry more of the experience.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open Eco v2 app shell placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 app shell redesign with reduced header and navigation footprint\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image of the Eco v2 app shell redesign.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Layout Paradigm\n\nEco v2 introduced documented page layout paradigms, giving teams predictable, reusable structures that improved usability and sped up delivery across products.\n\n- Standardized 1-, 2-, and 3-column responsive layouts for consistency.\n- Defined Index / Workspace / Inspector model to support complex workflows.\n- Reduced reliance on ad-hoc layouts, replacing them with clear conventions.\n- Improved adaptability across screen sizes while preserving hierarchy.\n- Provided guidance on when to use each layout, reducing design and dev ambiguity.\n- Delivered implicit responsive benefits, as the defined paradigms scale smoothly from desktop to tablet and mobile.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      The layout paradigm work gave teams a shared structural language. That reduced rework and made\n      decisions about composition faster because teams were no longer starting from an empty canvas.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open layout paradigm placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 documented layout paradigms across 1, 2, and 3-column patterns\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image showing Eco v2 layout paradigms.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Exemplar Designs\n\nTo help teams apply Eco v2 consistently, we created exemplar designs that demonstrate how the new layout paradigms work in practice. These examples provided strong reference points across product sectors, reducing ambiguity and accelerating adoption.\n\n- Built exemplar flows showing synchronized components such as filters, maps, and data tables working together.\n- Demonstrated how Index, Workspace, and Inspector scale across 1-, 2-, and 3-column layouts.\n- Provided reference patterns for common cross-product needs, including dashboards, configuration flows, and approval workflows.\n- Helped unify experiences across Energy, Agriculture, and Weather products by showcasing best-practice compositions.\n- Reduced design drift by giving teams polished, ready-to-use examples as starting points.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      Exemplar designs turned the system into something teams could apply confidently, not just reference\n      abstractly. They accelerated adoption by showing complete compositions in real product contexts.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open exemplar designs placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 exemplar designs across DTN product sectors\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image of exemplar design patterns in use.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## From Design to Code\n\nThe migration to ShadCN and integration with the Design Registry enable rapid concept creation and validation directly in V0, ensuring ideas can move quickly from design to working code while staying aligned to Eco standards.\n\n- ShadCN components provide a lean, extensible foundation for product teams.\n- Design Registry manages governance, versioning, and consistency across the suite.\n- V0 integration allows quick prototyping and validation directly against Eco v2.\n- Exemplar designs act as launch points that can be refined into code through prompts.\n- Shortens the loop between design and development, accelerating iteration while preserving system integrity.\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      This workflow shift was as important as the visual redesign. Eco v2 made it easier for teams to move\n      from concept to code without breaking system standards or creating additional maintenance burden.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open design to code workflow placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 design-to-code workflow using ShadCN, Design Registry, and V0\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image showing the Eco v2 design-to-code workflow.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Why Eco v2 Matters\n\nEco v2 is not just a visual update but a UX-led redesign, built in partnership with developers to reshape how products are built and maintained. The system addresses usability, accessibility, and layout consistency, while also reducing developer friction through ShadCN, semantic tokens, and the Design Registry.\n\n- Captured and resolved both user and developer pain points from Eco v1.\n- Introduced systemic design and technical improvements rather than isolated fixes.\n- Provided exemplar patterns to guide consistent design and implementation across product sectors.\n- Integrated into the development pipeline, supporting rapid prototyping in V0.\n- Balanced speed, maintainability, and governance to ensure long-term scalability.\n\nEco v2 now serves as a foundation that improves delivery velocity, lowers technical debt, and aligns design and development within a shared system.\n\n## Gallery\n\n<div class=\"masonry-gallery\">\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 1\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder gallery image for Eco v2.</em></p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 2\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 3\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 4\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</div>","src/content/work/eco-v2-redesign.md","d8bd80d6fbcf91b0",{html:92,metadata:93},"<h2 id=\"problem--goal\">Problem + Goal</h2>\n<p><strong>User Problem:</strong> Designers and developers need a cleaner, more usable system with consistent patterns, better visuals, and easier extensibility.</p>\n<p><strong>Business Goal:</strong> Accelerate product delivery and reduce technical debt with a lean, modern design system that scales across DTN’s products.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-development-challenges-of-eco-v10\">The Development Challenges of Eco v1.0</h2>\n<p>While it established initial consistency, the system was rigid, bloated, and lacked the polish and patterns needed for scalable product design.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wrapped Tailwind UI components introduced bloat and rigidity.</li>\n<li>Component wrappers depended on Eco team-defined props, which meant developers could not extend or adjust behavior without waiting on the system team.</li>\n<li>Overrides were cumbersome, creating friction in day-to-day workflows.</li>\n<li>Rigid structure slowed iteration and encouraged shadow libraries.</li>\n<li>Heavy documentation burden: significant effort was needed to document customization and workarounds, adding maintenance overhead.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      These constraints made Eco v1 difficult to scale in practice. Even when teams wanted to stay aligned\n      with the design system, the developer ergonomics often pushed them toward local exceptions and\n      one-off workarounds.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open Eco v1 development challenges placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v1 component wrapper and developer workflow challenges\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image illustrating Eco v1 development constraints or component wrapper complexity.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"the-design-challenges-of-eco-v10\">The Design Challenges of Eco v1.0</h2>\n<p>From a design perspective, Eco v1 suffered from foundational gaps that made products feel inconsistent, cluttered, and difficult to use.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>No page layout conventions: products defaulted to ad-hoc app shells and inconsistent content structures.</li>\n<li>Visual bloat: oversized headers, navigation, and excessive padding consumed valuable viewport space.</li>\n<li>Poor color accessibility: insufficient contrast and inconsistent application of accessible color standards.</li>\n<li>Lack of exemplar designs: teams had no strong reference patterns, leading to drift and uneven quality.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      Without strong layout paradigms and exemplars, product teams had too much interpretive freedom in\n      the wrong places. The result was inconsistency in both usability and visual quality across the suite.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open Eco v1 design challenges placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v1 layout inconsistency and visual bloat examples\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image showing Eco v1 visual clutter, spacing issues, or inconsistent layouts.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"component-system-revamp\">Component System Revamp</h2>\n<p>In Eco v2 we rebuilt our component system around ShadCN-based components, maintaining Eco’s core styling for easier product adoption while addressing major gaps in flexibility, accessibility, and polish. The revamp not only simplified the developer experience but also raised the design quality across all products.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ShadCN foundation: lean, extensible components aligned to modern front-end workflows (still based on Tailwind CSS) without custom wrappers and associated bloat.</li>\n<li>Eco styling preserved: ensured continuity with v1 while enabling smoother product conversion.</li>\n<li>Polish improvements: redefined color palette, contrast, and spacing for better accessibility and visual clarity.</li>\n<li>Cleaned-up components: simplified props, reduced bloat, and eliminated redundant wrappers.</li>\n<li>Design Registry integration: improved governance, supporting both ground-up development and streamlined use with V0.</li>\n<li>Future-ready pipeline: positioned Eco for faster iteration, lower technical debt, and broader cross-product consistency.</li>\n<li>Introduced semantic tokens for color, typography, and spacing, improving consistency across components and enabling easier theming and accessibility compliance.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"appshell-revamp\">Appshell Revamp</h2>\n<p>The Eco v2 app shell was redesigned to maximize usable workspace and improve accessibility, while still providing clear navigation and hierarchy. The new shell establishes a cleaner baseline for all products.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reduced footprint of the header and navigation, creating more space for core content.</li>\n<li>Refined color contrast in both light and dark modes for improved readability and compliance with accessibility standards.</li>\n<li>Simplified information hierarchy, reducing visual noise and redundant elements.</li>\n<li>Improved product suite portal experience with streamlined app switching, unified cross-app notifications, and a more consistent navigation model across products.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      The updated app shell created a stronger baseline for every product team. By reducing chrome and\n      clarifying hierarchy, Eco v2 made room for content and workflows to carry more of the experience.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open Eco v2 app shell placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 app shell redesign with reduced header and navigation footprint\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image of the Eco v2 app shell redesign.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"layout-paradigm\">Layout Paradigm</h2>\n<p>Eco v2 introduced documented page layout paradigms, giving teams predictable, reusable structures that improved usability and sped up delivery across products.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Standardized 1-, 2-, and 3-column responsive layouts for consistency.</li>\n<li>Defined Index / Workspace / Inspector model to support complex workflows.</li>\n<li>Reduced reliance on ad-hoc layouts, replacing them with clear conventions.</li>\n<li>Improved adaptability across screen sizes while preserving hierarchy.</li>\n<li>Provided guidance on when to use each layout, reducing design and dev ambiguity.</li>\n<li>Delivered implicit responsive benefits, as the defined paradigms scale smoothly from desktop to tablet and mobile.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      The layout paradigm work gave teams a shared structural language. That reduced rework and made\n      decisions about composition faster because teams were no longer starting from an empty canvas.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open layout paradigm placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 documented layout paradigms across 1, 2, and 3-column patterns\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image showing Eco v2 layout paradigms.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"exemplar-designs\">Exemplar Designs</h2>\n<p>To help teams apply Eco v2 consistently, we created exemplar designs that demonstrate how the new layout paradigms work in practice. These examples provided strong reference points across product sectors, reducing ambiguity and accelerating adoption.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Built exemplar flows showing synchronized components such as filters, maps, and data tables working together.</li>\n<li>Demonstrated how Index, Workspace, and Inspector scale across 1-, 2-, and 3-column layouts.</li>\n<li>Provided reference patterns for common cross-product needs, including dashboards, configuration flows, and approval workflows.</li>\n<li>Helped unify experiences across Energy, Agriculture, and Weather products by showcasing best-practice compositions.</li>\n<li>Reduced design drift by giving teams polished, ready-to-use examples as starting points.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      Exemplar designs turned the system into something teams could apply confidently, not just reference\n      abstractly. They accelerated adoption by showing complete compositions in real product contexts.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open exemplar designs placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 exemplar designs across DTN product sectors\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image of exemplar design patterns in use.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"from-design-to-code\">From Design to Code</h2>\n<p>The migration to ShadCN and integration with the Design Registry enable rapid concept creation and validation directly in V0, ensuring ideas can move quickly from design to working code while staying aligned to Eco standards.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ShadCN components provide a lean, extensible foundation for product teams.</li>\n<li>Design Registry manages governance, versioning, and consistency across the suite.</li>\n<li>V0 integration allows quick prototyping and validation directly against Eco v2.</li>\n<li>Exemplar designs act as launch points that can be refined into code through prompts.</li>\n<li>Shortens the loop between design and development, accelerating iteration while preserving system integrity.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <p>\n      This workflow shift was as important as the visual redesign. Eco v2 made it easier for teams to move\n      from concept to code without breaking system standards or creating additional maintenance burden.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open design to code workflow placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 design-to-code workflow using ShadCN, Design Registry, and V0\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a right-aligned image showing the Eco v2 design-to-code workflow.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"why-eco-v2-matters\">Why Eco v2 Matters</h2>\n<p>Eco v2 is not just a visual update but a UX-led redesign, built in partnership with developers to reshape how products are built and maintained. The system addresses usability, accessibility, and layout consistency, while also reducing developer friction through ShadCN, semantic tokens, and the Design Registry.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Captured and resolved both user and developer pain points from Eco v1.</li>\n<li>Introduced systemic design and technical improvements rather than isolated fixes.</li>\n<li>Provided exemplar patterns to guide consistent design and implementation across product sectors.</li>\n<li>Integrated into the development pipeline, supporting rapid prototyping in V0.</li>\n<li>Balanced speed, maintainability, and governance to ensure long-term scalability.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Eco v2 now serves as a foundation that improves delivery velocity, lowers technical debt, and aligns design and development within a shared system.</p>\n<h2 id=\"gallery\">Gallery</h2>\n<div class=\"masonry-gallery\">\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 1\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder gallery image for Eco v2.</em></p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 2\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 3\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: Eco v2 gallery image 4\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</div>",{headings:94,localImagePaths:121,remoteImagePaths:122,frontmatter:123,imagePaths:124},[95,96,99,102,105,108,111,114,117,120],{depth:29,slug:30,text:31},{depth:29,slug:97,text:98},"the-development-challenges-of-eco-v10","The Development Challenges of Eco v1.0",{depth:29,slug:100,text:101},"the-design-challenges-of-eco-v10","The Design Challenges of Eco v1.0",{depth:29,slug:103,text:104},"component-system-revamp","Component System Revamp",{depth:29,slug:106,text:107},"appshell-revamp","Appshell Revamp",{depth:29,slug:109,text:110},"layout-paradigm","Layout Paradigm",{depth:29,slug:112,text:113},"exemplar-designs","Exemplar Designs",{depth:29,slug:115,text:116},"from-design-to-code","From Design to Code",{depth:29,slug:118,text:119},"why-eco-v2-matters","Why Eco v2 Matters",{depth:29,slug:71,text:72},[],[],{title:83,year:15,industry:84,category:85,summary:86,thumbnail:87,featured:20},[],"eco-v2-redesign.md","patient-intake-experience",{id:126,data:128,body:135,filePath:136,digest:137,rendered:138,legacyId:147},{title:129,year:130,industry:131,category:132,summary:133,thumbnail:134,featured:20},"Patient Intake Experience",2024,"HealthTech","Service Design","Mapped end-to-end service touchpoints to improve completion and reduce administrative overhead.","/images/sample-wind-farm.png","The intake journey spanned digital forms, staff handoffs, and in-person checkpoints.\n\nI mapped service touchpoints to find friction between systems and teams, then proposed an intake model with clearer status visibility and fewer redundant steps.\n\nThe result was improved form completion rates and less manual rework for front-desk staff.\n\n## Gallery\n\n<div class=\"masonry-gallery\">\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-wind-farm.png\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 1\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 2\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 3\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 4\" />\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</div>","src/content/work/patient-intake-experience.md","b8941f10135d9440",{html:139,metadata:140},"<p>The intake journey spanned digital forms, staff handoffs, and in-person checkpoints.</p>\n<p>I mapped service touchpoints to find friction between systems and teams, then proposed an intake model with clearer status visibility and fewer redundant steps.</p>\n<p>The result was improved form completion rates and less manual rework for front-desk staff.</p>\n<h2 id=\"gallery\">Gallery</h2>\n<div class=\"masonry-gallery\">\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-wind-farm.png\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 1\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 2\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 3\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"masonry-item\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb\">\n      <img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Patient Intake gallery image 4\">\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</div>",{headings:141,localImagePaths:143,remoteImagePaths:144,frontmatter:145,imagePaths:146},[142],{depth:29,slug:71,text:72},[],[],{title:129,year:130,industry:131,category:132,summary:133,thumbnail:134,featured:20},[],"patient-intake-experience.md","experiments",["Map",150,151,170,171],"decision-confidence-indicators",{id:150,data:152,body:158,filePath:159,digest:160,rendered:161,legacyId:169},{title:153,year:15,area:154,summary:155,thumbnail:156,featured:157},"Decision Confidence Indicators","UX Signals","Prototyped interface cues that communicate confidence in recommendations without overwhelming users.","/images/sample-stock-market.png",false,"This concept focused on trust calibration in recommendation-heavy interfaces.\n\nI tested lightweight confidence indicators, explanatory hover states, and reversible actions to reduce the fear of committing too early.\n\nThe resulting pattern set provided a clearer language for uncertainty while preserving a clean interaction flow.","src/content/experiments/decision-confidence-indicators.md","dad839582e0c7dd6",{html:162,metadata:163},"<p>This concept focused on trust calibration in recommendation-heavy interfaces.</p>\n<p>I tested lightweight confidence indicators, explanatory hover states, and reversible actions to reduce the fear of committing too early.</p>\n<p>The resulting pattern set provided a clearer language for uncertainty while preserving a clean interaction flow.</p>",{headings:164,localImagePaths:165,remoteImagePaths:166,frontmatter:167,imagePaths:168},[],[],[],{title:153,year:15,area:154,summary:155,thumbnail:156,featured:157},[],"decision-confidence-indicators.md","adaptive-onboarding-prompts",{id:170,data:172,body:178,filePath:179,digest:180,rendered:181,legacyId:189},{title:173,year:174,area:175,summary:176,thumbnail:177,featured:20},"Adaptive Onboarding Prompts",2026,"Product Intelligence","Tested whether adaptive prompt sequencing could reduce onboarding friction in high-choice workflows.","/images/sample-storm.png","This experiment explored how onboarding can change as users reveal intent signals.\n\nInstead of one static walkthrough, the prototype adapted prompts based on initial actions and skipped irrelevant guidance.\n\nThe output was a rules framework for adaptive onboarding logic that can be reused across products with different complexity profiles.","src/content/experiments/adaptive-onboarding-prompts.md","a4390b2a5480aa6e",{html:182,metadata:183},"<p>This experiment explored how onboarding can change as users reveal intent signals.</p>\n<p>Instead of one static walkthrough, the prototype adapted prompts based on initial actions and skipped irrelevant guidance.</p>\n<p>The output was a rules framework for adaptive onboarding logic that can be reused across products with different complexity profiles.</p>",{headings:184,localImagePaths:185,remoteImagePaths:186,frontmatter:187,imagePaths:188},[],[],[],{title:173,year:174,area:175,summary:176,thumbnail:177,featured:20},[],"adaptive-onboarding-prompts.md","musings",["Map",192,193,212,213,232,233,251,252],"interviewing-users-without-leading-them",{id:192,data:194,body:199,filePath:200,digest:201,rendered:202,legacyId:211},{title:195,publishDate:196,topic:197,summary:198,featured:20},"Interviewing Users Without Leading Them",["Date","2026-01-28T00:00:00.000Z"],"Research","Simple moderation shifts can dramatically improve research signal quality.","Leading prompts create false confidence and weak product decisions.\n\nI prefer neutral language, concrete follow-ups, and task reconstruction over opinion polling. This reveals real behavior and tradeoffs instead of aspirational answers.\n\nA small interview guide rewrite often improves signal more than recruiting more participants.","src/content/musings/interviewing-users-without-leading-them.md","a0632bea2f6d001b",{html:203,metadata:204},"<p>Leading prompts create false confidence and weak product decisions.</p>\n<p>I prefer neutral language, concrete follow-ups, and task reconstruction over opinion polling. This reveals real behavior and tradeoffs instead of aspirational answers.</p>\n<p>A small interview guide rewrite often improves signal more than recruiting more participants.</p>",{headings:205,localImagePaths:206,remoteImagePaths:207,frontmatter:208,imagePaths:210},[],[],[],{title:195,publishDate:209,topic:197,summary:198,featured:20},["Date","2026-01-28T00:00:00.000Z"],[],"interviewing-users-without-leading-them.md","design-critiques-that-actually-improve-work",{id:212,data:214,body:219,filePath:220,digest:221,rendered:222,legacyId:231},{title:215,publishDate:216,topic:217,summary:218,featured:157},"Design Critiques That Actually Improve Work",["Date","2025-11-07T00:00:00.000Z"],"Collaboration","A practical structure for critique sessions that sharpen decisions, not egos.","Critique quality is mostly a facilitation problem.\n\nWhen sessions anchor on goals, evidence, and constraints, feedback becomes actionable instead of subjective. I use a lightweight format that separates observation, interpretation, and recommendation.\n\nTeams leave with clearer decisions and faster iteration cycles.","src/content/musings/design-critiques-that-actually-improve-work.md","55b81f0563564f0a",{html:223,metadata:224},"<p>Critique quality is mostly a facilitation problem.</p>\n<p>When sessions anchor on goals, evidence, and constraints, feedback becomes actionable instead of subjective. I use a lightweight format that separates observation, interpretation, and recommendation.</p>\n<p>Teams leave with clearer decisions and faster iteration cycles.</p>",{headings:225,localImagePaths:226,remoteImagePaths:227,frontmatter:228,imagePaths:230},[],[],[],{title:215,publishDate:229,topic:217,summary:218,featured:157},["Date","2025-11-07T00:00:00.000Z"],[],"design-critiques-that-actually-improve-work.md","when-to-standardize-and-when-to-bend-the-rules",{id:232,data:234,body:238,filePath:239,digest:240,rendered:241,legacyId:250},{title:235,publishDate:236,topic:85,summary:237,featured:20},"When to Standardize and When to Bend the Rules",["Date","2025-12-19T00:00:00.000Z"],"Consistency matters, but rigid systems can become friction points if misapplied.","Design systems scale quality, but they should not block meaningful problem-solving.\n\nStandards work best when teams understand intent, not just component availability. For edge cases, intentional exceptions can preserve clarity and improve outcomes.\n\nA healthy system balances guardrails with room for context.","src/content/musings/when-to-standardize-and-when-to-bend-the-rules.md","9ae995a7f2aedd90",{html:242,metadata:243},"<p>Design systems scale quality, but they should not block meaningful problem-solving.</p>\n<p>Standards work best when teams understand intent, not just component availability. For edge cases, intentional exceptions can preserve clarity and improve outcomes.</p>\n<p>A healthy system balances guardrails with room for context.</p>",{headings:244,localImagePaths:245,remoteImagePaths:246,frontmatter:247,imagePaths:249},[],[],[],{title:235,publishDate:248,topic:85,summary:237,featured:20},["Date","2025-12-19T00:00:00.000Z"],[],"when-to-standardize-and-when-to-bend-the-rules.md","why-good-ux-starts-with-better-questions",{id:251,data:253,body:258,filePath:259,digest:260,rendered:261,legacyId:303},{title:254,publishDate:255,topic:256,summary:257,featured:20},"Why Good UX Starts With Better Questions",["Date","2026-02-12T00:00:00.000Z"],"Product Thinking","Framing assumptions early helps teams avoid expensive design detours later.","Strong UX outcomes are often decided before pixels are explored.\n\nWhen teams align on problem framing, constraints, and success criteria, design work moves faster with less churn.\n\nQuestion quality is a leverage point: better questions produce better options.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nTeams often treat design as the phase where answers appear. In practice, design quality is heavily shaped by the quality of the questions that come before solutioning starts.\n\nWeak questions create shallow options:\n\n- \"Can we make this page simpler?\"\n- \"Can we add AI here?\"\n- \"Can we move faster on onboarding?\"\n\nBetter questions produce better design decisions:\n\n- What job is the user trying to complete, and where does progress currently stall?\n- Which constraints are real, and which are inherited assumptions?\n- What decision will this screen help a user make?\n\n![Placeholder: question framing worksheet or whiteboard capture](/images/placeholder-thumb.svg)\n\n_Placeholder for a whiteboard photo, question map, or planning artifact._\n\n## A practical framing pattern (Text + Image Split)\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <h3>Start with decision quality, not feature scope</h3>\n    <p>\n      Before exploring flows, I want clarity on the decisions the product must support. If a team can\n      describe the decision, the actor, and the timing, the design space usually becomes easier to\n      navigate.\n    </p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>What choice needs to be made?</li>\n      <li>Who is making it?</li>\n      <li>What information is required to make it confidently?</li>\n      <li>What happens if the decision is delayed or wrong?</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open decision framing template placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-stock-market.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Decision framing template or canvas\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a simple framing canvas that ties decisions, actors, and constraints together.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## The questions I ask before wireframes\n\n### 1. What are we actually optimizing for?\n\nTeams often answer with a metric, but that is not enough. I also want to know what tradeoffs are acceptable and what quality bar matters to the business.\n\n### 2. What would success look like in user behavior?\n\nA strong answer describes behavior change, not just shipped output. It tells us what \"better\" should feel like in the user journey.\n\n### 3. Where is uncertainty highest right now?\n\nThis is usually where research, prototypes, or instrumentation can save the most time later.\n\n## Bad question vs better question (Comparison Block)\n\n| Common prompt | Better framing question |\n| --- | --- |\n| \"Can we redesign onboarding?\" | Which step in onboarding causes the highest abandonment, and what uncertainty causes it? |\n| \"Can we make the dashboard cleaner?\" | What decisions should the dashboard enable in the first 60 seconds? |\n| \"Can we add more personalization?\" | Which user segments need different defaults to complete the same job successfully? |\n\n## Example: from vague request to useful brief (Alternating Blocks)\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <h3>Initial request</h3>\n    <p>\n      \"Users are confused by the reporting area. We should redesign it.\"\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      This statement may be true, but it is too broad to guide meaningful design choices. It bundles\n      together comprehension, navigation, hierarchy, and expectation-setting into one vague problem.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open vague problem statement placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-storm.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Notes from an early vague problem statement\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for early notes showing broad, unstructured problem language.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <h3>Refined framing</h3>\n    <p>\n      \"Operations managers cannot identify which facilities need attention in under two minutes during\n      morning review. They lack clear prioritization signals and have to scan too many charts to find\n      risk.\"\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      This version gives design a usable target: who, when, what task, what failure mode, and what kind\n      of information hierarchy is missing.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open refined problem framing placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-wind-farm.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Refined brief or prioritized problem framing\" />\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a clearer brief with actors, timing, decision, and constraints highlighted.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n## Quick checklist for better questions\n\n- Define the user and the moment, not just the feature area\n- Name the decision the interface should support\n- Separate known constraints from assumptions\n- Clarify what tradeoffs are acceptable\n- Decide what evidence would change your mind\n\n## A lightweight team exercise (Process Snapshot)\n\n1. Write the problem statement in one sentence.\n2. Underline every vague term (`better`, `cleaner`, `intuitive`, `smart`, `streamlined`).\n3. Replace each vague term with observable behavior or a decision outcome.\n4. List the top 3 constraints (technical, operational, regulatory, or timeline).\n5. Agree on what will be measured after release.\n\n> Better design questions do not slow teams down. They reduce wasted motion by making the design work more directional from the start.\n\n## Closing thought\n\nDesign is often judged by artifacts, but the leverage starts earlier. The teams that ask better questions produce stronger options, make tradeoffs faster, and ship work that holds up longer.","src/content/musings/why-good-ux-starts-with-better-questions.md","d3e55d3f0ad2bed4",{html:262,metadata:263},"<p>Strong UX outcomes are often decided before pixels are explored.</p>\n<p>When teams align on problem framing, constraints, and success criteria, design work moves faster with less churn.</p>\n<p>Question quality is a leverage point: better questions produce better options.</p>\n<h2 id=\"why-this-matters\">Why this matters</h2>\n<p>Teams often treat design as the phase where answers appear. In practice, design quality is heavily shaped by the quality of the questions that come before solutioning starts.</p>\n<p>Weak questions create shallow options:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>“Can we make this page simpler?”</li>\n<li>“Can we add AI here?”</li>\n<li>“Can we move faster on onboarding?”</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Better questions produce better design decisions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What job is the user trying to complete, and where does progress currently stall?</li>\n<li>Which constraints are real, and which are inherited assumptions?</li>\n<li>What decision will this screen help a user make?</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src=\"/images/placeholder-thumb.svg\" alt=\"Placeholder: question framing worksheet or whiteboard capture\"></p>\n<p><em>Placeholder for a whiteboard photo, question map, or planning artifact.</em></p>\n<h2 id=\"a-practical-framing-pattern-text--image-split\">A practical framing pattern (Text + Image Split)</h2>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <h3>Start with decision quality, not feature scope</h3>\n    <p>\n      Before exploring flows, I want clarity on the decisions the product must support. If a team can\n      describe the decision, the actor, and the timing, the design space usually becomes easier to\n      navigate.\n    </p>\n    <ul>\n      <li>What choice needs to be made?</li>\n      <li>Who is making it?</li>\n      <li>What information is required to make it confidently?</li>\n      <li>What happens if the decision is delayed or wrong?</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open decision framing template placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-stock-market.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Decision framing template or canvas\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a simple framing canvas that ties decisions, actors, and constraints together.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"the-questions-i-ask-before-wireframes\">The questions I ask before wireframes</h2>\n<h3 id=\"1-what-are-we-actually-optimizing-for\">1. What are we actually optimizing for?</h3>\n<p>Teams often answer with a metric, but that is not enough. I also want to know what tradeoffs are acceptable and what quality bar matters to the business.</p>\n<h3 id=\"2-what-would-success-look-like-in-user-behavior\">2. What would success look like in user behavior?</h3>\n<p>A strong answer describes behavior change, not just shipped output. It tells us what “better” should feel like in the user journey.</p>\n<h3 id=\"3-where-is-uncertainty-highest-right-now\">3. Where is uncertainty highest right now?</h3>\n<p>This is usually where research, prototypes, or instrumentation can save the most time later.</p>\n<h2 id=\"bad-question-vs-better-question-comparison-block\">Bad question vs better question (Comparison Block)</h2>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<table><thead><tr><th>Common prompt</th><th>Better framing question</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>”Can we redesign onboarding?”</td><td>Which step in onboarding causes the highest abandonment, and what uncertainty causes it?</td></tr><tr><td>”Can we make the dashboard cleaner?”</td><td>What decisions should the dashboard enable in the first 60 seconds?</td></tr><tr><td>”Can we add more personalization?”</td><td>Which user segments need different defaults to complete the same job successfully?</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2 id=\"example-from-vague-request-to-useful-brief-alternating-blocks\">Example: from vague request to useful brief (Alternating Blocks)</h2>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <h3>Initial request</h3>\n    <p>\n      \"Users are confused by the reporting area. We should redesign it.\"\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      This statement may be true, but it is too broad to guide meaningful design choices. It bundles\n      together comprehension, navigation, hierarchy, and expectation-setting into one vague problem.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open vague problem statement placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-storm.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Notes from an early vague problem statement\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for early notes showing broad, unstructured problem language.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"cs-split\">\n  <div>\n    <h3>Refined framing</h3>\n    <p>\n      \"Operations managers cannot identify which facilities need attention in under two minutes during\n      morning review. They lack clear prioritization signals and have to scan too many charts to find\n      risk.\"\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      This version gives design a usable target: who, when, what task, what failure mode, and what kind\n      of information hierarchy is missing.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"cs-split-media\">\n    <button type=\"button\" class=\"detail-gallery-thumb cs-split-thumb\" aria-label=\"Open refined problem framing placeholder\">\n      <img src=\"/images/sample-wind-farm.png\" alt=\"Placeholder: Refined brief or prioritized problem framing\">\n    </button>\n    <p class=\"cs-split-caption\"><em>Placeholder for a clearer brief with actors, timing, decision, and constraints highlighted.</em></p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"quick-checklist-for-better-questions\">Quick checklist for better questions</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Define the user and the moment, not just the feature area</li>\n<li>Name the decision the interface should support</li>\n<li>Separate known constraints from assumptions</li>\n<li>Clarify what tradeoffs are acceptable</li>\n<li>Decide what evidence would change your mind</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"a-lightweight-team-exercise-process-snapshot\">A lightweight team exercise (Process Snapshot)</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Write the problem statement in one sentence.</li>\n<li>Underline every vague term (<code>better</code>, <code>cleaner</code>, <code>intuitive</code>, <code>smart</code>, <code>streamlined</code>).</li>\n<li>Replace each vague term with observable behavior or a decision outcome.</li>\n<li>List the top 3 constraints (technical, operational, regulatory, or timeline).</li>\n<li>Agree on what will be measured after release.</li>\n</ol>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Better design questions do not slow teams down. They reduce wasted motion by making the design work more directional from the start.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"closing-thought\">Closing thought</h2>\n<p>Design is often judged by artifacts, but the leverage starts earlier. The teams that ask better questions produce stronger options, make tradeoffs faster, and ship work that holds up longer.</p>",{headings:264,localImagePaths:298,remoteImagePaths:299,frontmatter:300,imagePaths:302},[265,268,271,274,277,280,283,286,289,292,295],{depth:29,slug:266,text:267},"why-this-matters","Why this matters",{depth:29,slug:269,text:270},"a-practical-framing-pattern-text--image-split","A practical framing pattern (Text + Image Split)",{depth:29,slug:272,text:273},"the-questions-i-ask-before-wireframes","The questions I ask before wireframes",{depth:42,slug:275,text:276},"1-what-are-we-actually-optimizing-for","1. What are we actually optimizing for?",{depth:42,slug:278,text:279},"2-what-would-success-look-like-in-user-behavior","2. What would success look like in user behavior?",{depth:42,slug:281,text:282},"3-where-is-uncertainty-highest-right-now","3. Where is uncertainty highest right now?",{depth:29,slug:284,text:285},"bad-question-vs-better-question-comparison-block","Bad question vs better question (Comparison Block)",{depth:29,slug:287,text:288},"example-from-vague-request-to-useful-brief-alternating-blocks","Example: from vague request to useful brief (Alternating Blocks)",{depth:29,slug:290,text:291},"quick-checklist-for-better-questions","Quick checklist for better questions",{depth:29,slug:293,text:294},"a-lightweight-team-exercise-process-snapshot","A lightweight team exercise (Process Snapshot)",{depth:29,slug:296,text:297},"closing-thought","Closing thought",[],[],{title:254,publishDate:301,topic:256,summary:257,featured:20},["Date","2026-02-12T00:00:00.000Z"],[],"why-good-ux-starts-with-better-questions.md"];

